04119nam a22006735i 9780813550954DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135509547 a10.36019/97808135509542doi  a(DE-B1597)529309  a(OCoLC)768082561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBM755 .M94 .A3 2011 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a296.61086643a296.7140922731 aMyers, Andrea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Choosing :bA Rabbi's Journey from Silent Nights to High Holy Days /cAndrea Myers. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA young Lutheran girl grows up on Long Island, New York. She aspires to be a doctor, and is on the fast track to marriage and the conventional happily-ever-after. But, as the Yiddish saying goes, "Man plans, and God laughs." Meet Andrea Myers, whose coming-of-age at Brandeis, conversion to Judaism, and awakening sexual identity make for a rich and well-timed life in the rabbinate. In The Choosing, Myers fuses heartwarming anecdotes with rabbinic insights and generous dollops of humor to describe what it means to survive and flourish on your own terms. Portioned around the cycle of the Jewish year, with stories connected to each of the holidays, Myers draws on her unique path to the rabbinate--leaving behind her Christian upbringing, coming out as a lesbian, discovering Judaism in college, moving to Israel, converting, and returning to New York to become a rabbi, partner, and parent. Myers relates tales of new beginnings, of reinventing oneself, and finding oneself. Whether it's a Sicilian grandmother attempting to bake hamantaschen on Purim for her Jewish granddaughter, or an American in Jerusalem saving a chicken from slaughter during a Rosh Hashanah ritual, Myers keeps readers entertained as she reflects that spirituality, goodness, and morality can and do take many forms. Readers will enthusiastically embrace stories of doors closing and windows opening, of family and community, of integration and transformation. These captivating narratives will resonate and, in the author's words, "reach across coasts, continents, and generations."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJewish converts from ChristianityxBiographyxUnited States. 0aJewish converts from ChristianityzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aLesbian rabbisxBiographyxUnited States. 0aLesbian rabbiszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355095440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813550954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813550954/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK